T []\nxref: EC:2.1.1.357 {source=\"skos:exactMatch\"}\nxref: RHEA:60308 {source=\"skos:exactMatch\"}\nis_a: GO:0046975 ! histone H3K36 methyltransferase activity\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/22588\" xsd:anyURI\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/30193\" xsd:anyURI\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/30578\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2022-11-01T15:06:50Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0140955\nname: histone H3K36 trimethyltransferase activity\nnamespace: molecular_function\ndef: \"Catalysis of the reaction: L-lysyl36-[histone H3] + 3 S-adenosyl-L-methionine = 3 H+ + N6,N6,N6-trimethyl-L-lysyl36-[histone H3] + 3 S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine. This reaction is the successive addition of three methyl groups to the lysine residue at position 36 of histone H3, producing histone H3K36me3.\" [RHEA:60324]\ncomment: Comment: Note that the residue position corresponds to the canonical human H3 histone (UniProtKB:P84243); this residue is conserved across all eukaryotes. Residue 1 is the first residue following removal of the initiating Methionine (Met). Note that each histone is encoded by multiple genes, and sequences may vary across different genes within an organism.\nsynonym: \"histone H3-K36 trimethylation\" BROAD []\nsynonym: \"histone H3K36 mono/di/trimethylase activity\" EXACT []\nsynonym: \"histone H3K36 trimethylase activity\" EXACT []\nsynonym: \"histone H3K36 trimethylation\" BROAD []\nsynonym: \"histone lysine N-trimethyltransferase activity (H3-K36 specific)\" EXACT []\nxref: EC:2.1.1.359 {source=\"skos:exactMatch\"}\nxref: RHEA:60324 {source=\"skos:exactMatch\"}\nis_a: GO:0046975 ! histone H3K36 methyltransferase activity\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/22588\" xsd:anyURI\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/30193\" xsd:anyURI\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/30578\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2022-11-01T15:18:59Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0140981\nname: medium-chain fatty acid omega-hydroxylase activity\nnamespace: molecular_function\ndef: \"Catalysis of the reaction: an omega-methyl-medium-chain fatty acid + O2 + reduced [NADPH--hemoprotein reductase] = an omega-hydroxy-medium-chain fatty acid + H+ + H2O + oxidized [NADPH--hemoprotein reductase]. A medium-chain fatty acid has an aliphatic tail containing 6 to 12 carbons.\" [RHEA:75279]\ncomment: While there is not universal consensus on the lengths of short-, medium-, long- and very-long-chain fatty acids, the GO uses the definitions in ChEBI (see CHEBI:26666, CHEBI:59554, CHEBI:15904 and CHEBI:27283).\nxref: MetaCyc:RXN-19719\nxref: RHEA:38947 {source=\"skos:narrowMatch\"}\nxref: RHEA:75279 {source=\"skos:exactMatch\"}\nxref: RHEA:75283 {source=\"skos:narrowMatch\"}\nis_a: GO:0120250 ! fatty acid omega-hydroxylase activity\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/24661\" xsd:anyURI\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/26445\" xsd:anyURI\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/30193\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2023-01-10T14:42:33Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0140989\nname: 7-deoxyloganate 7-hydroxylase activity\nnamespace: molecular_function\ndef: \"Catalysis of the reaction: 7-deoxyloganate + O2 + reduced [NADPH-hemoprotein reductase] = H+ + H2O + loganate + oxidized [NADPH-hemoprotein reductase].\" [PMID:24710322, RHEA:57576]\nxref: EC:1.14.14.85 {source=\"skos:broadMatch\"}\nxref: RHEA:57576 {source=\"skos:exactMatch\"}\nis_a: GO:0016712 ! oxidoreductase activity, acting on paired donors, with incorporation or reduction of molecular oxygen, reduced flavin or flavoprotein as one donor, and incorporation of one atom of oxygen\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/24838\" xsd:anyURI\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/30193\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2023-02-01T09:58:39Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141035\nname: CTP-dependent diacylglycerol kinase activity\nnamespace: molecular_function\ndef: \"Catalysis of the reaction: a 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol + CTP = a 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphate + CDP + H+.\" [RHEA:25948]\nsynonym: \"DAG kinase activity\" BROAD [EC:2.7.1.174]\nsynonym: \"diacylglycerol kinase (CTP dependent)\" BROAD [EC:2.7.1.174]\nsynonym: \"diacylglycerol kinase activity\" BROAD []\nsynonym: \"diacylglycerol kinase activity (CTP)\" EXACT []\nxref: EC:2.7.1.174 {source=\"skos:exactMatch\"}\nxref: KEGG_REACTION:R09944\nxref: MetaCyc:RXN-12959\nxref: RHEA:25948 {source=\"skos:exactMatch\"}\nis_a: GO:0001727 ! lipid kinase activity\nis_a: GO:0016773 ! phosphotransferase activity, alcohol group as acceptor\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/25280\" xsd:anyURI\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/30193\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2023-04-18T07:14:42Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141050\nname: histone H3K deacetylase activity\nnamespace: molecular_function\ndef: \"Removal of an acetyl group from a lysine residue in a histone H3.\" [GOC:pg, PMID:9893272]\ncomment: Histone deacytylase (HDAC) enzymes are divided into four classes: the Class I Rpd3-like proteins (in human: HDAC1, HDAC2, HDAC3, and HDAC8); the Class II Hda1-like proteins (in human: HDAC4, HDAC5, HDAC6, HDAC7, HDAC9, and HDAC10); the Class III Sir2-like proteins (in human: SIRT1, SIRT2, SIRT3, SIRT4, SIRT5, SIRT6, and SIRT7); and the Class IV protein (HDAC11 in human). Except for Class III enzymes, the mechanism is a metal-dependent hydrolysis of the acetylated substrate. The Class III HDACs use NAD+ as a reactant to deacetylate acetyl lysine residues of protein substrates forming nicotinamide, the deacetylated product, and the metabolite 2'-O-acetyl-ADP-ribose. Therefore, Class III are classified as transferases (EC:2) and others are hydrolases (EC:3).\nxref: EC:2.3.1.- {source=\"skos:broadMatch\"}\nxref: EC:3.5.1.- {source=\"skos:broadMatch\"}\nis_a: GO:0004407 ! histone deacetylase activity\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/22836\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2024-09-20T11:40:05Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141051\nname: histone H4K deacetylase activity\nnamespace: molecular_function\ndef: \"Removal of an acetyl group from a lysine residue in a histone H4.\" [PMID:12590135]\ncomment: Histone deacytylase (HDAC) enzymes are divided into four classes: the Class I Rpd3-like proteins (in human: HDAC1, HDAC2, HDAC3, and HDAC8); the Class II Hda1-like proteins (in human: HDAC4, HDAC5, HDAC6, HDAC7, HDAC9, and HDAC10); the Class III Sir2-like proteins (in human: SIRT1, SIRT2, SIRT3, SIRT4, SIRT5, SIRT6, and SIRT7); and the Class IV protein (HDAC11 in human). Except for Class III enzymes, the mechanism is a metal-dependent hydrolysis of the acetylated substrate. The Class III HDACs use NAD+ as a reactant to deacetylate acetyl lysine residues of protein substrates forming nicotinamide, the deacetylated product, and the metabolite 2'-O-acetyl-ADP-ribose. Therefore, Class III are classified as transferases (EC:2) and others are hydrolases (EC:3).\nxref: EC:2.3.1.- {source=\"skos:broadMatch\"}\nxref: EC:3.5.1.- {source=\"skos:broadMatch\"}\nis_a: GO:0004407 ! histone deacetylase activity\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/25508\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2023-06-07T09:15:53Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141098\nname: tRNA (cytidine(34)-2'-O-ribose)-methyltransferase activity\nnamespace: molecular_function\ndef: \"Catalysis of the reaction: cytidine(34) in tRNA + S-adenosyl-L-methionine = 2'-O-methylcytidine(34) in tRNA + H+ + S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine.\" [PMID:31943105, RHEA:43084]\nsynonym: \"tRNA (cytidine 34-2'-O)-methyltransferase activity\" EXACT []\nsynonym: \"tRNA (cytidine(34)-2'-O)-methyltransferase activity\" EXACT []\nxref: EC:2.1.1.207 {source=\"skos:broadMatch\"}\nxref: MetaCyc:RXN-11860 {source=\"skos:exactMatch\"}\nxref: RHEA:43084 {source=\"skos:exactMatch\"}\nis_a: GO:0016427 ! tRNA (cytidine) methyltransferase activity\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/26084\" xsd:anyURI\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/30714\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2023-09-11T13:53:59Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141102\nname: tRNA (5-carboxymethylaminomethyluridine(34)-2'-O-ribose)-methyltransferase activity\nnamespace: molecular_function\ndef: \"Catalysis of the reaction: 5-carboxymethylaminomethyluridine34 in tRNA(Leu) + S-adenosyl-L-methionine = 5-carboxymethylaminomethyl-2'-O-methyluridine34 in tRNA(Leu) + H+ + S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine.\" [PMID:20855540, RHEA:43088]\nsynonym: \"tRNA (5-carboxymethylaminomethyluridine(34)-2'-O)-methyltransferase activity\" EXACT []\nsynonym: \"tRNA (cytidine(34)/5-carboxymethylaminomethyluridine(34)-2'-O)- methyltransferase activity\" EXACT []\nxref: EC:2.1.1.207 {source=\"skos:broadMatch\"}\nxref: RHEA:43088 {source=\"skos:exactMatch\"}\nis_a: GO:0016300 ! tRNA (uridine) methyltransferase activity\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/26145\" xsd:anyURI\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/30193\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2023-09-19T10:47:21Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141126\nname: short-chain fatty acyl-CoA hydrolase activity\nnamespace: molecular_function\ndef: \"Catalysis of the reaction: a short-chain fatty acyl-CoA + H2O = a short fatty acid + CoA + H+. A short-chain fatty acid has an aliphatic tail of less than 6 carbons.\" [RHEA:68180]\ncomment: While there is not universal consensus on the lengths of short-, medium-, long- and very-long-chain fatty acids, the GO uses the definitions in ChEBI (see CHEBI:26666, CHEBI:59554, CHEBI:15904 and CHEBI:27283).\nxref: EC:3.1.2.18 {source=\"skos:narrowMatch\"}\nxref: MetaCyc:3.1.2.18-RXN\nxref: RHEA:31251 {source=\"skos:narrowMatch\"}\nxref: RHEA:40103 {source=\"skos:narrowMatch\"}\nxref: RHEA:40111 {source=\"skos:narrowMatch\"}\nxref: RHEA:40799 {source=\"skos:narrowMatch\"}\nxref: RHEA:45156 {source=\"skos:narrowMatch\"}\nxref: RHEA:55052 {source=\"skos:narrowMatch\"}\nxref: RHEA:55064 {source=\"skos:narrowMatch\"}\nxref: RHEA:55084 {source=\"skos:narrowMatch\"}\nxref: RHEA:55096 {source=\"skos:narrowMatch\"}\nxref: RHEA:65204 {source=\"skos:narrowMatch\"}\nxref: RHEA:65208 {source=\"skos:narrowMatch\"}\nxref: RHEA:66980 {source=\"skos:narrowMatch\"}\nxref: RHEA:66984 {source=\"skos:narrowMatch\"}\nxref: RHEA:68180 {source=\"skos:exactMatch\"}\nis_a: GO:0047617 ! fatty acyl-CoA hydrolase activity\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/26441\" xsd:anyURI\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/30193\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2023-12-08T09:05:55Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141131\nname: DNA N6-methyladenine demethylase activity\nnamespace: molecular_function\ndef: \"Catalysis of the reaction: 2-oxoglutarate + an N6-methyl-2'-deoxyadenosine in DNA + O2 = a 2'-deoxyadenosine in DNA + CO2 + formaldehyde + succinate.\" [RHEA:49524]\nsynonym: \"DNA N(6)-methyladenine demethylase activity\" EXACT []\nxref: EC:1.14.11.51 {source=\"skos:exactMatch\"}\nxref: RHEA:49524 {source=\"skos:exactMatch\"}\nis_a: GO:0016706 ! 2-oxoglutarate-dependent dioxygenase activity\nis_a: GO:0035514 ! DNA demethylase activity\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/26656\" xsd:anyURI\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/29802\" xsd:anyURI\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/30193\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2023-12-15T15:38:23Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141148\nname: enoyl-[acyl-carrier-protein] reductase (NADPH) activity\nnamespace: molecular_function\ndef: \"Catalysis of the reaction: a 2,3-saturated acyl-[ACP] + NADP+ = a (2E)-enoyl-[ACP] + H+ + NADPH.\" [RHEA:22564]\ncomment: This reaction completes each cycle of fatty acid elongation by catalyzing the stereospecific reduction of the double bond at position 2 of a growing fatty acid chain, while linked to the acyl- carrier protein, in an NADPH-dependent manner. Note that EC has reactions describing the stereo-specificity of the reaction with respect to NADP+ (cf. EC 1.3.1.39, EC 1.3.1.10 and EC 1.3.1.104).\nxref: EC:1.3.1.10 {source=\"skos:narrowMatch\"}\nxref: EC:1.3.1.104 {source=\"skos:exactMatch\"}\nxref: EC:1.3.1.39 {source=\"skos:narrowMatch\"}\nxref: MetaCyc:ENOYL-ACP-REDUCT-NADPH-RXN {source=\"skos:exactMatch\"}\nxref: RHEA:22564 {source=\"skos:exactMatch\"}\nxref: RHEA:41812 {source=\"skos:narrowMatch\"}\nis_a: GO:0016631 ! enoyl-[acyl-carrier-protein] reductase [NAD(P)H] activity\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/25699\" xsd:anyURI\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/28173\" xsd:anyURI\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/30035\" xsd:anyURI\ncreated_by: pg\ncreation_date: 2024-01-29T11:56:59Z\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0141152\nname: glycerol-3-phosphate dehydrogenase (NAD+) activity\nnamespace: molecular_function\ndef: \"Catalysis of the reaction: NAD+ + sn-glycerol 3-phosphate = dihydroxyacetone phosphate + H+ + NADH.\" [RHEA:11092]\nsynonym: \"alpha-glycerol p